column168: THE DRIVER FAILED TO ASSURE SECONDARY VAPOR RECOVERY CAP WAS SECURELY FASTENED.  DURING UNLOADING, THE CAP CAME OFF DUE TO PRESSURE OF NORMAL UNLOADING WHICH CAUSED GASOLINE TO SPRAY. THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL WILL BE RECYCLED AND THEN DISPOSED OF AT THE APPROVED DISPOSAL SITE.

THE DRIVER WAS FINISHING THE DELIVERY.  WHILE DRAINING SUCTION HOSE TO TRUCK'S PUMP, THE STORAGE TANK REACHED 90% LEVEL.  WHEN THE TANK STOPPED RECEIVING PRODUCT, PRESSURE BUILT UP IN THE PUMP DISCHARGE HOSE AND IT RUPTURED.  WHEN THE DRIVER SAW WHAT HAPPENED AND AFTER RECOVERING FROM BEING HIT BY THE DISCHARGE HOSE, HE SHUT THE PRODUCT OFF.  HE NOTIFIED THE COMPANY OFFICE, THE CLEAN UP WAS ARRANGED AND COMPLETED.  TO KEEP THIS INCIDENT FROM REOCCURING, TANKS SHOULD BE FILLED ONLY TO THE 80% LEVEL.

(BUTLY & PROPYL ALCOHOL), WAS OBSERVED LEAKING (DRIPPING) FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP/PLUG WHILE KCS CREW (THE NOAL, TRAIN #205431) WAS SWITCHING THE COWLEY SIDING TRACK AT KCS MILE POST D-75.  KCS TRAINMASTER, J.  OLIVER, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 1115 HOURS AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WITHOUT SUCCESS.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED THEIR RESPONSE TEAM, EMTECH ENVIRONEMTANL SERVICES, OUT OF FORT WORTH, TEXAS, TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  MR. TERRY ROCKWELL AND CHARLIE COOK, WITH EMTECH, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 1355 HOURS.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP/PLUG WAS TIGHTEN ONE FULL TURN SUCCESSFULLY STOPPING THE LEAK. EMTECH PERSONNEL INDICATED THAT THE TANK CAR, INCLUDING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP THREADS HAD BEEN RECENTLY PAINTED.  THE FRESH PAINT, ON THE PIPE THREADS, WAS DISSOLVED BY THE LADING (ALCOHOL) ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK BY THE PIPE THREADS.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 1405 HOURS THAT SAME DAY.

ON FEBRUARY 8, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 0320 HOURS, TANK CAR KCCX 2516, LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' MINDEN LOUISIANA RAILYARD.  THIS TANK CAR LEAKED ONLY WHEN MOVED.  THEREFORE, THIS CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO THE OLD SHOP LEAD TRACK TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE.  THE SHIPPER, KENNECOTT UTAH COPER CORP., WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION ON FEBRUARY 8, 1997, AT 0421 HOURS AND ARRANGED FOR REPAIRS.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES SUBSEQUENTLY REPLACED A DEFECTIVE RUPTURE DISK ON FEBRUARY 9, 1997, AND RELEASED THE TANK CAR FOR DESTINATION.

ON FEBRUARY 5, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HOURS, RAILROAD TANK CAR TEIX 1294, LOAD OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. (SODIUM SULFIDE SOLUTIONS SPENT, CONTAINING SODIUMHYDROXIDE) WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' LOUISIANA RAILYARD.  THE TANK CAR WOULD LEAK ONLY WHEN MOVED.  THEREFORE, THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO THE RIP TRACK TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE. THE SHIPPER, MERICHEM COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION AT 1600 HOURS.  MERICHEM COMPANY DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW TO EVALUATE THE CAR AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THE SHIPPERS RESPONSE CREW REPLACED A DEFECTIVE RUPTURED DISK CORRECTING THE LEAK.  ALL REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 1420 HOURS ON FEBRUARY 6,

column168: DMP AREA WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING FLAMMABLE LIQUID LEAKER.  AFTER CONSULTING THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET,  I PROCEEDED TO PD-5, WHILE WEARING PROPER PPE. BACK AT DMP AREA ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.

USING MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS I ISOLATED THE AREA AND CONTAINERIZED THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE BOX SO NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED.  I THEN BROUGHT BACK TO THE DMP AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.

I RECEIVED A CALL FROM PD-5 ABOUT A LEAKING CORROSIVE LIQUIDS PACKAGE.  I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET.  PROPER PPE WAS USED AND I NEUTRALIZED ACID TO PH READING OF 7.  CLEANED AREA AND RETURNED TO PSC AND PROCESSED THRU DMP PROGRAM.

TRAIN 1-799-01 WAS ADVISED OF A NATURAL GAS SMELL COMING FROM THE TRAIN AS IT PASSED ORWOOD, CA.  THE CREW CONTINUED WITH THE TRAIN TO A NON-POPULATED AREA AT PORT CHICAGO, BNSF MILE POST 1163.4, TO MAKE AN INSPECTION.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES ASSISTED BNSF PERSONEL WITH AN ASSESSMENT. THE LEAD FLAT CAR WAS TRANSPORTING CONTAINER NOSU 442707 WHICH CONTAINED 76 DRUMS OF ETHYL MERCAPTAN, A PUNGENT ODORIZER MOST COMMONLY USED IN NATURAL GAS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THIS CONTAINER, NO PRODUCT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING THROUGH TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTRA COSTA FIRE DEPT RELEASED THE TRAIN TO CONTINUE THE 25 MILES TO ITS DESTINATION WHERE THE CONTAINER COULD BE SAFELY LIFTED OUT OF THE WELL IN THE FLAT CAR AND FURTHER ASSESSED IN A PAVED AND LIGHTED AREA. ********************** THE CONTAINER WAS DERAMPED AND PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT CONTAINMENT PIT AT THE RICHMOND INTERMODAL FACILITY.  ONCE AT THE PIT, INSPECTION REVEALED NO EXTERNAL SIGNS OF LEAKAGE, BUT THE FOUL STENCH WAS STILL PRESENT.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THAT THEIR CONTRACTOR HANDLE THE LOAD AND REMEDIATION. IN ADDITION, THE BENEFICIAL OWNER DISPATCHED A TEAM TO ASSIST WITH THE RESOLUTION EFFORTS.  IN THE INTERIM, THE RICHMOND FIRE DEPT AND CONTRA COSTA COUNTY HEALTH DEPT ARRIVED AT THE PIT TO REVIEW PROGRESS AND PROVIDE INPUT TO THE RESOLUTION PLAN BEING DEVELOPED.  DUE TO CONCERNS ABOUT RELEASING ADDITIONAL ODOR, THE CONTAINER WAS NOT PERMITTED TO BE OPENED TO ASSESS THE CONDITION OF THE LOAD.  READINGS TAKEN ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINER WITH A COMBUSTIBLE GAS INDICATOR FOUND LEVELS SIGNIFICANTLY ABOVE THE LOWER EXPLOSIVE LIMIT (LEL) FOR THE PRODUCT. FOLLOWING A JOINT MEETING ON 2/5, THE CONTAINER WAS TAKEN FROM THE RAMP TO A REMOTE SITE FOR OPENING AND ASSESSMENT.  SEVERAL METHODS WERE ATTEMPTED TO CONTROL THE ODOR AND REDUCE THE VAPORS. **************************************** ENTRY WAS PERMITTED ON 2/6.  OVERALL, THE LOAD WAS IN GOOD CONDITION AND BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS SECURE.  ONE DRUM IN THE SECOND ROW FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO HAVE A THREE INCH LONG HAIRLINE CRACK IN THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE DRUM HAD BEEN ROTATING WHILE IN TRANSIT AND HAD WORN THE BOTTOM CHIME FLAT (FOR ABOUT A ONE-HALF INCH WIDE BY TWENTY-EIGHT INCH LONG LENGTH OF THE DRUM'S CIRCUMFERENCE) ON THE STEEL 'TUNNEL' PLATE IN THE CONTAINER FLOOR.  THIS PLATE ADDS REINFORCEMENT TO THE CONTAINER IN THE REGION WHERE A HITCH WOULD BE ON A TRAILER.  A SHIM BETWEEN THE PLATE AND DRUMS IS NOT USUALLY NECESSARY.  MOST OF THE 16 DRUMS IN THE FIRST FOUR STACKS HAD MARKS INDICATING ROTATION, THOUGH.  ALL DRUMS WERE CLEANED AND RELOADED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER FOR EXPORT.  THE CULPRIT DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPING FACILITY AT THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST.  RESULTS OF THE FLAT CAR'S RIDE QUALITY HAVE NOT BEEN FULLY EVALUATED.  ************** ITEM 23E PROVIDES TRAIN DELAY COST FOR SEVEN TRAINS DELAYED FOR THE INITIAL INSPECTION AT PORT CHICAGO.  THE COST INCLUDES LOST INCENTIVE PAYMENTS FOR TARDY OPERATION OF TWO AMT

TWO OF THE EXPORT PROCESSORS HELD AND QUESTIONED THIS SHIPMENT BECAUSE IT DID NOT HAVE ANY PAPERWORK TO SEND IT BACK TO WUH.  WHEN THIS SHIPMENT WAS OPENED, IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE TOXIC - THERE WAS A PIECE OF PAPER ATTACHED TO THE TWO CANISTERS THAT HAS THE TOXIC SYMBOL OF THE SKULL AND CROSSBONES WITH THE NUMBER #6 ON IT.  IT WAS ALSO DESCRIBED ON THE PAPER AS A MARINE POLLUTANT.  ALTHOUGH IT IS BELIEVED THAT NONE OF THE CONTENTS HAS LEAKED OUT OF CANISTERS, THE CANISTERS ARE GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR. THE SFO AIRPORT MANAGER HAS TAKEN STEPS TO CONTACT THE STATION MANAGER IN LIT TO FIND OUT WHY THEY WOULD SEND THIS SHIPMENT BACK TO US IN THE CONDITION THAT IT WAS IN.  DHL ALWAYS PROVIDES DANGEROUS GOODS CLASSES TO ITS EMPLOYEES AND ALSO HAS AVAILABLE INFORMATION IN WHAT TO DO WHEN A HAZMAT SHIPMENT ARISES.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD FINISHED BLENDING SODIUM CYANIDE AND WATER INTO SOLUTION. THE DRIVER WAS STARTING TO UNLOAD SOLUTION INTO CUSTOMER TANKS AT MINE. THE DRIVER EXPERIENCED A BLOCKAGE IN THE LINE AND COULD NOT UNLOAD.  AS DRIVER WAS SEEKING ASSISTANCE, THE LIQUID LEVELS OF THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANKS AND OUR CARGO TANK BEGAN TO EQUALIZE.  EVENTUALLY THE SOLUTION OVERFILLED THE CARGO TANK SPILLING SOME THROUGH THE OPEN DOME LID. SOLUTION WAS RECOVERED BY THE MINE SITE PERSONNEL AND ADDED BACK INTO THE MINING PROCESS.  A JOINT MEETING WAS HELD WITH THE MINE, SHIPPER, AND CARRIER REPRESENTATIVES TO IDENTIFY CAUSES AND PREVENTION METHODS. TRAINING AND PROCEDURES WERE UPDATED TO REFLECT CHANGES NEEDED FOR PREVENTION.

column168: THE DOCKMAN DISCOVERED DAMAGED PAIL ON THE OUTBOUND TRAILER.  SOMEWHERE IN HANDLING THE PAIL WAS STRUCK WITH OTHER FREIGHT CAUSING THE PAIL TO BE CRUSHED AND DENTED.  THE PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR AS THE SHIPPER DID NOT WANT THE PAIL BACK.  THE PAILS SHOULD ALWAYS BE PROTECTED FROM DAMAGE IN THE FREIGHT HANDLING PROCESS.

THE DOCKMAN WAS OPERATING A FORKLIFT CARRYING A PALLET WHICH HAD CARTONS STACKED ON THE PALLET.  THE CARTON FELL OFF THE PALLET AND THE FORKLIFT WHEELS STRUCK THE CARTON.  THE IMPACT CAUSED ONE OF THE GLASS BOTTLES TO BREAK INSIDE THE CARTON.  THE CARTON WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D WHERE THE BROKEN BOTTLE WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR AT A LATER DATE.  THE TWO GOOD BOTTLES WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR INSPECTION.  THE DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD ENSURE THAT CARTONS ARE SECURE ON PALLETS BEFORE MOVING.

CONSIGNEE UNLOADING, PRODUCT SPILLED INTO CONTAINMENT AREA, UNKNOWN THE CAUSE.

PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  DURING ROUTINE COMFORT STOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 40-50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  APPROX. 2 GALLONS ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER, THE MAJORITY OF WHICH WAS COLLECTED IN A CONTAINMENT PAIL PLACED UNDER THE VAN TRAILER UPON DISCOVERY OF THE RELEASE.  UPON ARRIVAL, PERSONNEL FROM OHM ENTERED THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  TOXI-SORB WAS THEN SPREAD ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL THAT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  IN ADDITION, THE OTHER CONTAINERS IN THE SHIPMENT WERE WIPED DOWN USING ABSORBENT PADS.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER REVEALED A PINHOLE LEAK APPROXIMATELY 6 INCHES FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER.
UNLOADING COMPLETED, PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF HOSE, INTO BUCKET, ALL CONTAINED.
PRODUCT BEING UNLOADED, WHEN VALVE STARTED TO LEAK, PRODUCT CONTAINED IN SPILL BUCKET.

SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO A POSSIBLE SPILL AT N-2 RAMP AT 0521L. UPON ARRIVAL RESPONSE TEAM FOUND A CORROSIVE SHIPMENT THAT HAD BEEN CRUSHED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DAMAGED SHIPMENT PLACED IN A 5 GALLON BUCKET IN THE WASTE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION BY ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS.

column168: ASSOCIATE UNLOADING TRAILER NOTICED STRONG ODOR.  THERE WAS SOME RESIDUE ON ONE OF THE CONTAINERS, BUT NO SIGNS OF LEAK.  POSSIBLE PACKAGING PROBLEM.  SHIPPER SENT SOMEONE OUT TO HANDLE CONTAINERS.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: WHEN ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER, CARTON WAS OPENED AND 2 ONE GALLON JUGS WERE BROKEN AND CONTENTS HAD EVAPORATED.  CARTON WAS NOT WET AND GAVE NO INDICATION OF EVER BEING WET.  IT IS UNKNOWN AS TO HOW OR WHEN JUGS WERE BROKEN.

BAG APPEARED TO HAVE SLID OFF THE TOP OF OTHER BAGS INSIDE OF PLASTIC COVERING OF PALLET DURING TRANSIT.  PLASTIC COVERING ON PALLET COULD HAVE BEEN A CLOSER FIT ON BAGS TO PREVENT SLIPPAGE.  ALSO, MORE DUNNAGE BETWEEN PALLETS WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE BAG FROM FALLING TO THE FLOOR OF TRAILER.
DRUM WAS STRUCK BY FORKLIFT, AND FREIGHT WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: IT APPEARS THAT FREIGHT WAS LEAKING AND DAMAGED WHEN LOADED ONTO TRAILER. THE FREIGHT WAS SCATTERED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE CARTONS WERE SOAKED.  WHEN THE FREIGHT WAS PICKED UP OFF THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, THE CARTONS ON THREE BOXES FELL APART.  THERE WAS LITTLE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER TO CAUSE THE AMOUNT OF DAMAGE TO THE CARTONS.
ASSOCIATE WAS UNLOADING THE DRUM, AND NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING AROUND THE BOTTOM.  DRUM HAD A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF IT.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A PAIL ON THE BOTTOM OF A SKID CREASED BECAUSE OF FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP OF PALLET OF PAILS.  LIQUID WAS SLIGHTLY OOZING FROM A HOLE IN THE CREASE.  PAIL WAS REMOVED FROM SKID AND PLACED IN POLY LINED RECOVERY PAIL.  RESIDUE WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED IN SAME RECOVERY PAIL.  OTHER PALLETS OF FREIGHT SHOULD NOT BE STACKED ON TOP OF PALLETS OF PAILS OF LIQUID.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DRUMS WERE BEING LOADED ONTO AN OUTBOUND TRAILER.  SOME WERE ALREADY LOADED WHEN HE CAME BACK WITH ANOTHER HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE DUNNAGE.  THE ONE THAT WAS LEAKING WAS TAKEN OUT ONTO THE DOCK AND TURNED OVER TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A LINED SALVAGE DRUM, OIL DRY WAS USED TO ABSORB THE LIQUID THAT HAD SPILLED AND IT WAS PLACED IN A LINED SALVAGE PAIL BOTH WERE PUT IN THE OS&D BAY AT LIT FOR HANDLING.

THEY INVESTIGATED AND FOUND ONE PAIL WITH SIGNS OF MINOR LEAKAGE AT THE TOP CAP.  THIS CAP WAS CHECKED AND IT WAS TIGHT.  THEY TIPPED THE PAIL AND THE LIQUID STARTED LEAKING AT THE SAME POINT UNDER THE CAP.  THERE WAS A VISIBLE RING ON PALLET WHERE A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED.  DAMAGED PAIL WAS OVERPACKED AND REMAINING PAILS WILL BE SHIPPED TO DESTINATION.

IT WAS THEN PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION.

DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING A SKID OFF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM WAS LOADED DIRECTLY BEHIND THE SKID WITH NO FORM OF BLOCKING TO PROTECT THE DRUM.  THE FORK WAS ABOUT SIX INCHES BEYOND THE SKID, AND IT PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  PROPER BLOCKING AND UNLOADING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE ACCIDENT. THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY LOADED INTO A 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL EXCESS MATERIAL INCLUDING THE QUICK DRY WAS SWEPT UP AND PUT INTO A SEPARATE DRUM.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS BACKING INTO THE DOCK, DRIVER SAID HE NOTICED EN ROUTE THE LEAK AND IMMEDIATELY RETURNED TO THE CUSTOMER CENTER TO SECURE THE DRUM. WHEN OPENING THE TRAILER THE DRUM WAS ON ITS SIDE LEAKING FROM A PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM.  WE REMOVED UNDAMAGED FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER AND SECURED THE DRUM IN A SALVAGEABLE CONTAINER AND CLEANED THE SPILLAGE UP, MOST OF IT HAD EVAPORATED BY ITSELF.

THE DOCKMAN NOTICED A TORN BAG WHEN HE GOT READY TO MOVE THE SKID.  IT LOOKED LIKE THE BAG RIPPED WHILE LOADING.  THE BAG WAS NOT BROKE OFF SKID. CARDBOARD WAS PUT ON ANOTHER SKID AND THE BAGS WERE PUT ON IT.  THE CARDBOARD WAS BROUGHT UP AROUND THE SIDE AND SHRINK WRAPPED IT TO KEEP IT FROM BLOWING ON ANYTHING ELSE.

THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN OFF TRAILER AND PLACED ON THE DOCK.  THE ASSOCIATE WAS SEARCHING FOR SECOND PIECE THAT GOES WITH FREIGHT.  HE NOTICED THAT THE CARTON WAS LEAKING AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR.  HE REALIZED THAT THE CARTON WAS PLACED DOWN TOO HARD ONTO CONCRETE.

A REFRIGERATOR HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF PALLET OF BAGS WITHOUT ANY TYPE OF PROTECTION OR DUNNAGE USED.  THE MOVEMENT DURING TRANSIT CAUSED THE BAGS TO TEAR AND SPILL.  THE SPILLED SOLID WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE PROPER LOADING AND USE OF DUNNAGE WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT.

DURING THE SORT, I FOUND THIS PACKAGE STAGED FOR INSPECTION.  ALL OF THE MARKINGS, LABELING, AND SHIPPER'S PAPERS APPEARED TO BE IN ORDER.  WHILE THERE WAS ONLY LITRE IN THE BOX, THE SIZE OF THE BOX I THOUGHT WAS EXTRAORDINARY. I DID GIVE THE SHIPPER SOME LATITUDE IN THAT OTHER NON HAZARDOUS MAY BE IN THE BOX.  I OPENED THE BOX, SAW LOTS OF PLASTIC PEANUTS AND GENTLY PUT MY HAND INTO THE PEANUTS.  I GRABBED WHAT I THOUGHT WAS A PLASTIC BOTTLE.  AS I PULLED IT STRAIGHT UP, I FOUND IT WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG WITH TWO OTHER BOTTLES.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER.  AS I WAS RETURNING FROM CALLING THE SHIPPER, THE BOTTLE OF ZINC CHLORIDE SOLUTION WAS DROPPED.  UPON HITTING THE CEMENT FLOOR, A SMALL CHIP OF THE CAP CAME OFF, ALLOWING ABOUT 3ML OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  THIS WAS NOT THE FAULT OF THE SHIPPER.  I SPOKE TO ALEX EVANS FROM THE FAA IN NASHVILLE.  THE FAA CHOSE NOT TO INSPECT IT AND RELEASED THE FREIGHT TO THE SHIPPER.  THE MATERIAL WAS REMOVED.
THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT CUSTOMER'S SITE.  THE PREMIUM TANK(UST) WAS A 3000 GALLON TANK.  THE TANK MEASURED AS HAVING 1283 GALLONS IN IT PRIOR TO THE DROP SO IT SHOULD HAVE HELD 1417 GALLONS IF FILLED TO THE 90% MARK OR 1717 GALLONS IF FILLED COMPLETELY.  OUR TRUCK HAD 1500 GALLONS IN THE COMPARTMENT DESIGNATED FOR THE TANK.  OUR COMPANY POLICY REQUIRES DRIVERS TO ATTEND THE TRUCK WHILE LOADING, FUELING, UNLOADING, OR ANYTIME IT IS LOADED.  ALL DRIVERS ARE REMINDED BY THE DISPATCHER TO STAND BY AT THIS TANK AT ALL TIMES,  BECAUSE OF ITS SIZE AND PRIOR PROBLEMS.  THE DRIVER HAD BEGUN UNLOADING PRODUCT AND THEN WALKED INTO THE STORE 50 - 75 FEET AWAY TO GET A CUP OF COFFEE.  HE WAS TALKING TO THE STORE CLERK WHEN THE TANK STARTED TO RUN OVER.  THE DRIVER WENT OUT AND SHUT THE TANK COMPARTMENT VALVES, STOPPING THE FLOW OF FUEL.  THE STORE CLERK CALLED THE FIRE DEPT TO COME AND PUT OUT FLOOR DRY AND ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP.  THEY RESPONDED  PROMPTLY AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION.  AFTER IT WAS ALL CONTAINED, THE DRIVER AND OTHER COMPANY PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND DISPOSED OF THEM IN ACCORDANCE WITH DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY INSTRUCTIONS.  ALL COMPANY PERSONNEL HAVE AGAIN BEEN TOLD OF THE IMPORTANCE OF STAYING WITH THEIR TRUCK AT ALL TIMES WHEN LOADING, FUELING, UNLOADING, OR ANYTIME IT IS LOADED.  THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS RELEASED FROM SERVICE DUE TO THE POLICY VIOLATION.
CUSTOMER WAS MOVING A SKID OF BAGS TO ONE SIDE(SHORT SKID).  FORKS WENT THROUGH AND PUNCTURED DRUM.  TURNED DRUM ON SIDE.  CALLED HAZMAT.

THE TOTE LOADED TO THE BACK HAD DEVELOPED A SMALL SEAM LEAK AND APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  WE HIRED A CLEAN-UP CREW WHO PUMPED PRODUCT INTO DRUMS AND CLEANED UP SPILL.  CUSTOMERS AGREED TO ACCEPT PRODUCT IN DRUMS.  THE LOAD FINISHED DELIVERY.

column168: THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT ST LOUIS, MO ON 2/20/97.  WHILE TRANSPORTING THIS TOTE ACROSS THE DOCK, THE DRIVER ACCIDENTALLY HIT THE VALVE ON THE TOTE WHILE REPOSITIONING IT.  THE TOTE IMMEDIATELY BEGAN DISPENSING.  THE SPILL WAS SURROUNDED BY A WALL OF OIL DRY.  ISK AND BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTACTED FOR ASSTSTANCE.  BODINE ENVIRONMENT SERVICES RESPONDED WITH A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAN UP CREW.  THE SPILL WAS SUCTIONED OFF THE DOCK INTO FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUMS.  THIS PROCESS TOOK APPROXIMATELY EIGHT HOURS TO COMPLETE.  THE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL DRUMS ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION.
NO DUNNAGE WAS USED TO PROTECT THE BAGS.  WHEN A PALLET OF LUMBER WAS LOADED BEHIND THE BAGS IT WAS PUSHED AGAINST AND RIPPED TWO OF THE BAGS. THE 2 BAGS WERE PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.

FOUR EYEBOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, FOUR EYEBOLTS WERE NOT POSITIONED IN THE HINGED MANWAY COVER.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN SERVICEABLE CONDITION.  ALL EYEBOLTS WERE PROPERLY POSITIONED AND TOOL TIGHTENED, USING THE STAR PATTERN.  SHIPPER NEGLECTED TO CORRECTLY SECURE CAR AT TIME OF LOADING.  THE CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT

EIGHT EYEBOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN SERVICEABLE CONDITION.  ALL EYEBOLTS WERE PROPERLY POSITIONED AND TOOL TIGHTENED, USING THE STAR PATTERN.  THE SHIPPER NEGLECTED TO CORRECTLY SECURE CAR AT TIME OF LOADING.

ONE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT OUR RELAY POINT GOODLAN, KS.  APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED IN TRANSIT DUE TO ROUGH ROAD CONDITION BOUNCING THE DRUM INTO OTHER FREIGHT.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CLEANUP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.

THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT OUR TERMINAL WITH A WET CARTON.  UPON INSPECTION, ONE PLASTIC JUG WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A LOOSE CAP.  THE ENTIRE CARTON WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM WITH LINER TO BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

TWO FIFTY POUND BAGS WERE DISCOVERED TORN WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER.  THE TWO BAGS HAD FALLEN IN TRANSIT CAUSING THEM TO SPLIT.  APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  BOTH TORN BAGS AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.

ONE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED WITH THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD A PALLET IN FRONT OF THE DRUM.  WHILE PLACING THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT UNDER THE PALLET, THE BRAKES ON THE FORKLIFT FAILED.  THE BLADES EXTENDED THROUGH THE PALLET AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE SPILLED.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE FORKLIFT WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL THE BRAKES COULD BE REPAIRED.

THE STATE HAZ MAT TEAM WERE CONTACTED BY PHONE AND STAYED ON LINE WITH THE DISTRICT MGR UNTIL SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL.  THERE WAS NO EVACUATION OF THE GENERAL PUBLIC, BUT THERE WAS A ROAD LEADING INTO A HOUSING DISTRICT OF 8 - 10 HOMES.  THE FIRE DEPT DID NOT ALLOW ANYONE TO LEAVE THE HOUSING DISTRICT OR COME INTO IT.  TOTAL EVAC TIME 6 HRS.   NO MAJOR ROADS BLOCKED ONLY ONE PERSON TRIED TO COME INTO HOUSE DIST AND HE WAS ALLOWED TO WALK IN - NO DRIVE CAR.

ITEM WAS A LEAKING 55 GALLON DRUM INSIDE 95 GALLON OVERPACK.  AS THE DRUM WAS BEING REMOVED FROM A TRAILER IT GOT CAUGHT ON THE DOOR.  THE DRUM COULD NOT BE FREED BY LIFTING.  AS THE DRUM WAS BEING LOWERED IT PROCEEDED TO TIP AND FALL OUT OF THE DRUM GRABBER.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR TRIED TO AVOID THIS BY BRINGING THE FORKS DOWN QUICKLY, BUT THE DRUM TIPPED AND FELL APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET.  WHEN IT LANDED, THE OVERPACK SPLIT ON BOTH SIDES, JUST UNDER THE FLANGE ON THE DRUM.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR MOVED THE FORKLIFT AROUND AND UPRIGHTED THE DRUM.  ACTIVITY STOPPED AND FACILITY EMPLOYEES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE SPILL SITE LOOKED SMALL, AND THE DRUM STOPPED LEAKING.  AFTER CALLING THE HEALTH AND SAFETY MANAGER, A HEALTH SAFETY PLAN WAS DEVELOPED AND WE PROCEEDED TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL. WE DISCOVERED THE AREA INVOLVED WAS LARGER THAN IT APPEARED BECAUSE THERE WAS A GRADE AND THE ACID TRAVELED UNDERNEATH THE GRAVEL.  CONTAMINATED GRAVEL WAS DRUMMED.  THERE WAS LITTLE SIGN OF ACID SOAKING INTO THE VERY HARD SOIL.  THE TOP INCH OF THE SOIL WAS DRUMMED.

THE DRIVER PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIAL AROUND THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO CATCH ANY OVERFLOW FROM THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT UNIT.  A CHIPPEWA TOWNSHIP POLICE OFFICER STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE, AND THE BEAVER COUNTY EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AT 10:47 AM.  THE BEAVER COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM PROVIDED OVERPACK/SALVAGE DRUM, AND PUMPED THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT UNIT INTO THE DRUM.  THE RELEASE DID NOT CONSTITUTE A RELEASE FROM A FACILITY AS ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE VAN/TRAILER.  THE FULL SHIPMENT, INCLUDING SPILLED MATERIAL PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM, WAS RETURNED TO THE CONSIGNOR.  HAZMAT RESPONDERS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGES HAD APPARENTLY FAILED BY PUNCTURE FROM A FORKLIFT WHILE LOADING AT THE CONSIGNOR'S SITE IN AMBRIDGE, PA.  IN ORDER TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS, DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO PROVIDE OVERSIGHT DURING ALL LOADING/UNLOADING OPERATIONS.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZ WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM SPIROL INTERNATIONAL LOCATED AT 321 REMMINGTON RD IN CUYAHOGA FALLS, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 S STONEY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT THE BUNG CAP HAD CORRODED ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT EACH CONTAINER ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION IS STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, ANY CONTAINER THAT IS NOT IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION IS TO BE EITHER TRANSFERRED INTO A NEW CONTAINER OR PLACED IN A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM BEFORE BEING ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

HE VERIFIED THAT THE DOME LID WAS STILL SECURE.  HE THEN TRANSPORTED THE CARGO TANKER BACK TO THE SHIPPER FACILITY (APPX 1/2 MILE).  THE FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY STARTED A CLEAN-UP PROJECT FOR ALL EFFECTED AREAS (NORTH NEW YORK STREET & 21ST STREET).  THE DEFECTIVE GASKETS HAVE BEEN REPLACED AND THIS SHOULD PREVENT ANY FUTURE SPILLS OF THIS NATURE.  ALL CARGO TANK INSPECTION TESTS WERE CURRENT.

column168: A FIRE ORIGINATED IN PREMISES #127 ON 1/31/97.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE.  SUBSEQUENTLY, ON THE MORNING OF 2/1/97 THERE WERE TWO SEPARATE FIRES AT PREMISES #216 AND #218.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT RESPONDED TO EACH OF THE SEPARATE INCIDENTS.  THE FIRE DEPT DID NOT NOTIFY FERRELLGAS UNTIL AFTER THE THIRD FIRE.  THE FIRE DEPT ULTIMATELY CONCLUDED THAT THE FIRES WERE APPARENTLY CAUSED BY LEAKING PROPANE GAS.  DUE TO THE HEAVY ODOR OF PROPANE GAS, LOCAL OFFICIALS ORDERED THE EVACUATION OF THE TENANTS IN THE UNITS ADJACENT TO THE AFFECTED UNITS.  A VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO PERFORM PROPANE VAPOR EXTRACTION FROM THE GROUND.  IN ADDITION, FERRELLGAS ENGAGED THE SERVICES OF A HAZ MAT RECOVERY FIRM WHO HAD BEEN AUTHORIZED BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES TO SUPERVISE AND OVERSEE THE EMERGENCY REMEDIATION.  ON 2/7/97 THE RESIDENCE WAS DETERMINED CLEAR (SUFFICIENT LEL CRITERIA) FOR ALL OCCUPANTS TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES.  DETERMINED FIRE WAS CAUSED BY A CRACK FLARE NUT IN THE GAS T-LINE SERVICING ONE OF THE BUILDINGS.  THE ENTIRE SECTION OF THIS PIPE AS WELL AS THE FITTINGS WAS SUBMITTED TO A METALLURGIST FOR REVIEW.

THIS WASTE STREAM IS A SOLID CONTAINING FILTER CAKE MATERIAL WITH CHROMIUM.  APPARENTLY THE MATERIAL WAS EITHER NOT PRESSED ENOUGH TO SQUEEZE THE LIQUID CONTENT OR SOMEHOW RAIN WATER GOT INTO THE CONTAINERS WHILE THEY WERE SITTING IN STORAGE.  THESE CONTAINERS WERE SUPERSACKS AND HENCE THE LEAK OCCURRED.  AS THE TRUCK ROLLED INTO THE OFFICE AREA THE LEAK WAS NOTICED.  THE TRUCK WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO A BURMED CONTAINED AREA AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED-UP USING OIL DRY.  IN THE FUTURE, GENERATOR IS GOING TO MAKE SURE THAT THE MATERIAL IS PRESSED ENOUGH TO GET THE EXTRA LIQUID CONTENT OUT.  ALSO, THE DRIVER WHILE DOING THE PICK-UP WILL CARRY SOME PLASTIC OR VISQUEEN AND WILL LOAD THESE SUPERSACKS ON IT TO CONTAIN ANY POTENTIAL RELEASE OF ADDITIONAL LIQUID CONTENT FROM THE CONTAINER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING EASTBOUND ON STATE HWY 58, EAST OF BORON CALIFORNIA.  HIS ATTENTION WAS DISTRACTED AWAY FROM HIS DRIVING AND HIS TRUCK DRIFTED OFF OF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO GET BACK ONTO THE ROAD AND MAINTAINED CONTROL OF THE TRUCK.  WHEN RE-ENTERING THE ROADWAY, HE OVERCORRECTED AND THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ONTO THE LEFT SIDE AND SLID APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET BEFORE COMING TO REST ACROSS BOTH LANES OF THE HIGHWAY.  ANOTHER DRIVER STOPPED TO HELP AND CALLED 911 AND THE TERMINAL MANAGER IN MOJAVE CALIFORNIA AT THE SHIPPERS PLANT.  WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER THE TRAILER RUPTURED ON THE WELDS OF THE FRONT THREE STIFFENER RINGS SURROUNDING THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER, AND AN OVERPRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS BROKEN AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE FERRIC CHLORIDE CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER LEAKED OUT AND RAN OFF OF THE ROADWAY INTO A DITCH OF THE WESTBOUND SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED DUE TO THE ACCIDENT FROM 0800 TO 1830 HOURS.  THE DRIVER RECEIVED BROKEN RIBS, A COLLAPSED LUNG AND FACIAL CUTS IN THE ACCIDENT.  HE WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK AND TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE.  THE PRODUCT IN THE DITCH WAS RECOVERED BY PUMPING IT INTO ANOTHER TRUCK BROUGHT TO THE SCENE, THEN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE RIGHTED AND TOWED TO THE IMPOUND YARD OF THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL IN BARSTOW CALIFORNIA.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  AFTER WE RECOVERED ALL OF THE PRODUCT POSSIBLE, THE CONTRACTOR REMOVED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, REPLACED IT WITH CLEAN SOIL, AND DISPOSED OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AT AN APPROVED WASTE SITE.  CORE SAMPLES TAKEN AT THE SITE PROVED TO TEST CLEAN AND WERE APPROVED BY SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY HEALTH SERVICES HAZMAT SO THE CONTAMINATION AREA COULD BE CLOSED PERMANENTLY.  THE VEHICLE COMBINATION WAS RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL AND THE DRIVER IS CONVALESCING UNDER HIS DOCTOR'S CARE.  IT IS EXPECTED THAT THE DRIVER WILL RETURN TO WORK AFTER HIS RECOVERY IS COMPLETED.

column168: MARATHON OIL COMPANY'S (MARATHON) CARGO TANK WAS STRUCK FROM BEHIND BY TRANSPORT EXPRESS'S CARGO TANK ON THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF HIGHWAY 1 APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES SOUTH OF MARSHALL, IL.  MARATHON'S CARGO TANK WAS CARRYING 9000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, MARATHON'S CARGO TANK RUPTURED AND A FIRE IGNITED THE CARGO TANK.  THE MARSHALL FIRE PROTECTION DISTRICT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE OF MARATHON'S CARGO TANK AND PREVENTED TRANSPORT EXPRESS'S CARGO FROM IGNITING.  THE REMAINING GASOLINE WAS REMOVED FROM MARATHON'S CARGO TANK AND TRANSPORTED TO MARATHON'S ROBINSON,,IL TERMINAL BY BOLIN ENTERPRISES, INC.  THE BURNT CARGO TANK WAS REMOVED FROM THE HIGHWAY AND TRANSPORTED TO A SALVAGE YARD.  THE BURNT SOILS IN THE DRAINAGE DITCH LOCATED ADJACENT TO THE HIGHWAY WERE REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED BY ADVANCED WASTE MANAGEMENT TO THE VICTORY LANDFILL IN TERRE HAUTE, IN FOR DISPOSAL AS A SPECIAL WASTE.

column168: CENTURY PETROLEUM DRIVER LOADED MORE ONTO TRUCK THAN WAS DISPATCHED. THIS CAUSED THE UNDERGROUND TANK TO OVERFILL AND SPILL ONTO THE PARKING LOT. THE APPROXIMATE AMOUNT OF THE SPILL IS 65 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. WHEN NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL WE IMMEDIATELY SENT THREE EMPLOYEES TO THE SITE AND PREVENTED THE SPILL FROM SPREADING. WE CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORB BOOMS, PADS, PILLOWS, AND CLAY MATERIAL. ALL WAS DISPOSED OF IN A LOCAL, LINED LANDFILL. TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLS OUR DRIVER WERE RE-TRAINED ON LOADING PROCEDURES AND ALSO ON HOW TO REACT IN THE EVENT OF A SPILL. THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SPILL RESIGNED TO AVOID PENDING DISCIPLINARY ACTION. I FEEL LIKE OUR CURRENT DRIVERS REALIZE THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPER LOADING AND HANDLING PROCEDURES. AS WELL AS HOW SERIOUS EVEN A SMALL SPILL CAN BE TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND TO OUR BUSINESS.

THIS IS A LATE REPORT - DRIVERS REPORTED TO THEIR FACILITY MANAGER AT CARRIER AND CARRIER CALLED SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY LINE (SEE-COPY-ASHLAND COMPANY FORM-) CARRIER FACILITY MANAGER PREPARED REPORTS AND MAILED, BUT THEY WERE APPARENTLY LOST ENROUTE TO THIS CORPORATE OFFICE. WE "DISCOVERED" THE INCIDENT UPON RECEIPT OF ASHLAND CHEMICAL COMPANY'S CLAIM 8/5/97 - AND INVESTIGATED -- CUSTOMER UNLOADER ATTEMPTED TO OBTAIN SAMPLE AND WHEN HE REMOVED THE END CAP FROM THE TRAILER OUTLET - PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT AND SPRAYED THE EYES OF MATTHEW WINFIELD, PLANT WORKER. HE RECLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE OF TRAILER AND WENT TO THE SHOWER. INVESTIGATION INDICATES THE INTERNAL VALVE OF THE TANK TRUCK MAY HAVE BEEN LEFT OPEN BY SHIPPER, AND DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY CHECK TRUCK PRIOR TO LEAVING SHIPPER'S PLANT. CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEES PERFORMED CLEANUP OPERATION. THE INJURED WORKER WAS TREATED FOR EYE IRRITATION. BUT DID NOT MISS WORK DAYS.

column168: ON 2/11/97 A GASOLINE ODOR WAS REPORTED BY HAZ MAT SUPV, TERRY CAIN.  THE LOCATION OF THE ODOR WAS LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177 AT THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY.  HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND THREE FIBERBOARD BOXES ONE OF WHICH WAS LEAKING.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE BOX IT WAS FOUND THAT THE OUTER BOX WAS NOT LEAKING.  THE INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS REVEALED THAT ONE METAL RECEPTACLE WAS LEAKING BECAUSE OF A LOOSE CLOSURE.  THERE WAS APPX 2 OZS THAT LEAKED.  TWO BOXES CONTAINED 2 RECEPTACLES EACH AND ONE BOX CONTAINED 1 RECEPTACLE.  THE BOX THAT CONTAINED 1 RECEPTACLE LEAKED.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL WITH THE SHIPMENTS, HOWEVER, THE INNER RECEPTACLES WERE BLOCKED WITH CARDBOARD SEPARATORS.  THESE BOXES WERE MARKED, LABELED AND THE HAZ MAT CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  THESE BOXES WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM WITH ALL MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 020197 AT APPX 230 PM GEOFFREY REEDER WAS NOTIFIED BY MGR TRAIN OPERATIONS, STAN BUBELA, THAT THIS CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER FOUND PRODUCT STREAMING ALONG WITH THE CENTER SILL.  THE CAR HAS AN ALUMINUM TANK THAT IS SUPPORTED ABOVE THE CENTER SILL BY TWO METAL PLATES.  BETWEEN THE TWO PLATES THE CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A SUMP. THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE HAD VIBRATED ITS BRACKET ENOUGH TO ALLOW IT TO CONTACT THE SIDE OF THE SUMP.  THE VIBRATION OF THE PIPE HAD CAUSED A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE SUMP.  THE HOLE COULD NOT BE REACHED TO ATTTEMPT A REPAIR.  THE SPRING VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT RESPONDED WITH A CATCH BASIN FOR THE PRODUCT.  TRANSPORT TRUCKS WERE CALLED AND THE LOAD TRANSFERRED TO THEM.  THE TRANSFER WAS CONDUCTED BY EMTECH AND WAS COMPLETED ABOUT 7 AM. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

ON 020297 AT APPX 3 PM GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MGR TRAIN OPERATIONS, CARL BROUGHTON THAT THIS CAR WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER FOUND LIQUID FLOWING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. REEDER CONTACTED EMTECH EMERGENCY SERVICE TO BRING A TRUCK TO REMOVE PRODUCT AND STOP THE RELEASE.  REEDER ALSO CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR INSTRUCTIONS ON THE DISPOSITION OF THE PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO THE TRUCK. THE SHIPPER ASKED THAT AT TOTAL OF 4000 GALS OF PRODUCT BE REMOVED AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE BY TRUCK.  AFTER THIS WAS COMPLETED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

AGENT BOUDREAUX CHECKED THE CAR TO DETERMINE IF THERE WAS ANY PRESSURE INSIDE THE CAR.  NONE WAS FOUND.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED AND THE GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE THE WRONG SIZE. AGENT BOUDREAUX CLOSED THE MANWAY COVER AND INSTRUCTED YARDMASTER JOE KASS TO MOVE THE TANK CAR TO A SAFE LOCATION TO MAKE REPAIRS. ******************* AGENT BOUDREAUX CONTACTED CHEMTREC'S CHRIS YOUNG FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION. AFTER REPAIRS WERE MADE, THE CAR WAS REMOVED TO CHECK FOR MANWAY LEAKS.  NO LEAKS WERE FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BY IBARRA FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: THE DRIVER OF A LIQUID PETROLEUM TANKER WAS IN THE PROCESS  OF FILLING A RESIDENCE'S PROPANE TANK.  UPON COMPLETION OF FILLING THE TANK AND CLOSURE OF THE FILL VALVE, THE FILLER HOSE RUPTURED TO A HOLE OF ABOUT 1/4", ALLOWING THE DISCHARGED OF SEVEN GALLONS OF LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS. IMMEDIATELY THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN ALL VALVES ELIMINATING FURTHER DISCHARGE. A VAPOR CLOUD OF PROPANE DRIFTED WITH THE WIND AND IGNITED.  THE SOURCE OF IGNITION WAS APPARENTLY FROM THE PILOT LIGHT ON A HOT WATER HEATER LOCATED WITHIN AN OUTSIDE LOUVERED DOOR OF THE RESIDENCE.  THE ENSUING FLASH FROM THE IGNITED PROPANE VAPOR CAUSED MODERATE DAMAGE TO THE RESIDENCES VINYL SIDING AND PROPERTY.  IMMEDIATELY THE DRIVER EXTINGUISHED SMALL FIRES WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER FROM THE TANKER AND CONTACTED HIS COMPANY WHOM IN TURN DISPATCHED A LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO BRIEFLY EXAMINED THE SCENE AND RESIDENCE.  NO ONE WAS INJURED.  A COMPANY SERVICE MAN WAS DISPATCHED TO INSPECT AND REPLACE PROPANE COMPONENTS WHERE NECESSARY.  A COMPANY SAFETY MAN ALSO INSPECTED THE SITE.  THE OCCUPANTS OF THE RESIDENCE REMAINED IN THEIR HOME THE ENTIRE TIME AND WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE HOT WATER TANK ALL GAS APPLIANCES WERE FUNCTIONAL.  NO ONE WAS EVACUATED.  TO PREVENT FUTURE ABRASION PROBLEMS RELATED INCIDENTS, THE HOSE WAS REPLACED AT ONCE AND ABRASION ROLLERS MAY BE INSTALLED TO ALLEVIATE HOSE WEAR.  FORMAL, SCHEDULED VISUAL INSPECTIONS OF HOSES AND A COMPLETE REVIEW OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE THE TOPIC OF A 2/13/97 SPECIAL SAFETY MEETING PERTINENT TO THIS INCIDENT.

ON 02/11/97 AT 1030 HRS, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, R L CARMAN WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR PTLX 223824 WAS LEAKING IN TRACK 302 IN THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK RAILYARD.  UPON ARRIVAL, SAHM CARMAN WAS ADVISED THAT UNION PACIFIC MECHANICAL FOREMAN, MIKE AVERY HAD REPORTEDLY TIGHTENED SOME LOOSE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER AND BELIEVED THE PROBLEM HAD BEEN RESOLVED.  SAHM CARMAN INSPECTED PTLX 223824 AND DETECTED AN ODOR ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR, BUT COULD NOT DETERMINE IF THE ODOR WAS A RESULT OF THE LOOSE BOLTS. ON 02/12/97 AT 0330 HRS, SAHM CARMAN WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC PERSONNEL IN MEMPHIS THAT THE CONDUCTOR OF TRAIN NLMECCX 11 REPORTED PTLX 223824 STILL HAVING AN ODOR. DONNIE HARRISON OF GREEN BAY PACKING ADVISED SAHM CARMAN THAT HE WOULD HAVE SOMEONE RESPOND AND CHANGE THE MANWAY GASKET.  HARRISON REPORT THAT PULP MILL LIQUID GIVES OFF AN OFFENSIVE ODOR, BUT THE ODOR ITSELF IS NOT HARMFUL.  HARRISON ADVISED THE PRODUCT IS PLACARDED BECAUSE OF ITS FLAMMABILITY. ******************************** ON 02/12/97 AT 1500 HRS, SAHM CARMAN WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE CONDUCTOR REPORTED BECOMING SICK AFTER SMELLING THE ODOR COMING FROM THE TANK CAR.  HE WAS EXAMINED AND RECEIVED A PRESCRIPTION.  ON 02/14/97 AT 1400 HRS SAHM CARMAN CONTACTED DAN SCHRECKENGOST OF RESCAR INC IN MEMPHIS. column168: LINEHAUL DRIVER WAS ENROUTE FROM ST. LOUIS, MO TO KEOKUK, IA AND STOPPED IN LA GRANGE, MO TO CHECK ON LOAD SINCE IT CONTAINED HAZMAT FREIGHT.  HE NOTICED AN ODOR AND INSPECTED FREIGHT AND NOTICED THAT FREIGHT HAD SHIFTED AND PUNCTURED A SMALL HOLE IN THE TOP OF THE TOTE OF DAMAGED SHIPMENT 667-648682.  HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED LINEHAUL IN ANN ARBOR, MI, WHO IN TURN CONTACTED ME, JOE WEISE.  ANOTHER DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE WITH SODA ASH TO ABSORB THE LEAK.  ONCE THE DAMAGE WAS SECURED, THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT TO KEOKUK, IA FOR HANDLING AND CLEANUP.

AT 11:45 A.M. JUNE HALE CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE AND HARMFULL STOW AWAY FROM FOODSTUFF RESPONSE SHEET. SHE THEN PLACED ON PROPER PPE. INCLUDING AN APRON, BOOTS, GLOVES, GOGGLES AND SLEEVE SHIELDS. CONTENTS WERE REFUSED BY THE SHIPPER. SHE THEN SOLIDIFIED THE ENTIRE FIVE GALLONS OF DICHLOROMETHANE WITH SPEEDY DRI. ALL CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM. THIS IS A THREE PART DMP. NO SPILL SITE SO NO CLEANUP WAS NEEDED.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY MIKE JOHNSON, MANAGER, ADMINSTRATIVE, ICTF FACILITY LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA, ADVISING HE HAD INSPECTED A LEAKING CONTAINER THAT SHOWED THE CONTENTS AS FAK (FREIGHT ALL KINDS).  HIS INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE CONTENTS TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF A COMMODITY THAT REQUIRED FLAMMABLE LABELS ON THE DRUMS.  AS THE RAIL PAPER WORK SHOWED THE CONTENTS AS FAK, HE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND REQUESTED AN ORIGINAL BILL OF LADING BE FAXED TO THE ICTF FOR VERIFICATION OF THE CONTENTS.  AS THE CONTAINER HAD FLAMMABLE PLACARDS APPLIED, IT WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMER DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING FURTHER INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF FACILITY AND CONTACTED CSX INTERMODAL, WHICH HAS AN OFFICE ON THE PROPERTY.  INFORMATION WAS OBTAINED THAT SHOWED THE CONTENTS AS ALUMINUM CHELATE AND ALUMINUM ALKOXIDE, ALL IN 55 GALLON DRUMS.  INSPECTION OF THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER REVELAED ONE OF THE PRODUCTS WAS LEAKING THROUGH THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER FLOORING.  INTERIOR INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE DRUMS TO BE FLOOR LOADED IN A 3X3 PATTERN, WITH THE 4TH DRUM OFF SET TO PICK UP THE VOID SPACE.  THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING OF ANY KIND TO SECURE THE DRUMS.  IN THE NOSE AREA OF THE CONTAINER, 4 DRUMS HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF THE FLOOR LOADED DRUMS TO PREVENT THE SECOND TIER DRUMS FROM SHIFTING TOWARDS THE REAR DOORS.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  IN THAT ENTIRE FLOOR AREA WAS COVERED WITH THE PRODUCT, IT WAS DIFFICULT TO DETERMINE THE LOCATION AND SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MITSUI TO PROVIDE AND EMPTY 20 FOOT CONTAINER, AS THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS SCHEDULED FOR EXPORT TO JAPAN, AND THERE WAS AN ISSUE WITH THE FLOORING BEING CONTAMINATED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, MAKING IT'S USE QUESTIONABLE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES REPRESENTATIVES LOCATED AT THE UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING AN OUTSIDE DRIVER HAD ATTEMPTED TO PICK UP A CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE OBSERVED A DARK LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE NOSE AREA OF THE CONTAINER.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #6, AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY, AND, UPON INSPECTING THE CONTAINER, OBSERVED A DAMP AREA AT THE RIGHT FRONT NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, HOWEVER THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK AT THE TIME OF THE INITIAL INSPECTION. IT WAS APPARENT THAT SOME OF THE LADING HAD LEAKED AS THE FLOORING WAS DAMP IN THIS LOCATION, AS WELL AS THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE CONTAINER FRAME.  THE RIGHT REAR DOOR SEAL, PARAGON 24411 AND REMOVED IN ORDER TO OPEN DOORS AND INSPECT THE LADING.  SEVERAL PIECES OF 2x4 LUMBER HAD BEEN PLACED IN A CRISSCROSS PATTERN AT THE BULL SLOTS BY THE REAR DOORS, AND SEVERAL USED PALLETS HAD BEEN PLACE ON END TO SECURE THE LADING.  4 CARTONS WERE IMMEDIATELY LOCATED ON TOP OF A LARGE WOOD CRATE TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER AT REAR DOORS, WHICH WERE IDENTIFIED AS A PORTION OF THE 6 LISTED FLAMMABLE COMMODITIES.  THE OTHER 2 CARTONS COULD NOT BE LOCATED.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THESE CARTONS WERE LAYING LOOSE WITH NO FORM OF SECUREMENT, OR SEGREGATION FROM THE OTHER LADING.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED FORM OF SECUREMENT, NOR IS IT AN APPROED METHOD PER BOE 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: ON 2/18/96, A STEERING FAILURE RESULTED WITH "OVERTURN" OF TANKER TRUCK AT THE LOCATION NOTED AS FOLLOWS: ROUTE 376 EASTBOUND PITTSBURGH/PA EXIT 5-FORBUS AVE. QUALIFIED INVESTIGATION INCLUDE MULTI MEDIA/AGENCY RESPONSE TO ESTABLISH CORRECTIVE ACTIONS UNDER DIRECTIVES OF PA/DEP, POINT OF CONTACT, PATTY MILLER, 412-596-0566. CLOSURE OF LANES IN BOTH DIRECTIONS IS REQUIRED TO CONDUCT FIRE SUPPRESSION SERVICES AND ABATE THREAT TO PUBLIC HEALTH AND SAFETY. THE ACCIDENT RESULTED WITH TOTAL LOSS OF PHYSICAL POWER UNIT AND TANK CARRIAGE. ** THE SPILL IS ESTIMATED 500 GALLONS WITH THE BALANCE OF LIQUID PRODUCT INCINERATED. NO NEGATIVE AND/OR ADVERSE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS NOTED BASED ON EMERGENCY RESPONSE EFFORTS. ** THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT IS UNDERSTOOD SUBJECT TO EQUIPMENT FAILURE AND LOCKING OF MECHANICAL STEERING OF THE POWER UNIT. PROCESS REVIEW AND EVALUATION WITH KEY PERSONNEL IS CONDUCTED TO MITIGATE AND PREVENT ANY FURTHER OCCURRENCE.  **  WE ENCLOSE PHOTOGRAPHS OF IN PROGRESS RESPONSE WORK TO ILLUSTRATE SITE SPECIFIC CONDITIONS AND COMPLETE YOUR PERMANENT RECORD.
